Solid ClF$_{3}$ is known to exist in several structures (Villars, 2018): \begin{itemize} \item From $-83^\circ$C to the melting point it has a \href{current_web_home_dir/AB3_mP32_14_2e_6e-001}{monoclinic structure with 16 formula units in the primitive cell}. \item Between $-109$ and $-100^{\circ}$C it takes on this orthorhombic structure. \item Below $-109^{\circ}$C there is another structure for which we have no data. \item (Villars, 2018) give no data on the structure between $-100$ and $-83^{\circ}$C. \end{itemize} ~ \vspace{-.25in} 
 \href{https://scibabe.com/daily-mos-the-unharnessed-chlorine-trifluoride/}{ClF$_{3}$ is extremely dangerous} in any of these forms. 
 \href{current_web_home_dir/AB3_oP16_62_c_cd-001}{Cementite ($D0_{11}$, Fe$_{3}$C)} and \href{current_web_home_dir/AB3_oP16_62_c_cd-005}{orthorhombic ClF$_{3}$} share the same AFLOW prototype label, AB3\_oP16\_oP16\_c\_cd. They are generated by the same symmetry operations with different sets of parameters ({\tt --params}) specified in their corresponding CIF files.
